This year the city of Whittlesea will be celebrating Children's Week with a host of child centred experiences at Westfield Plenty Valley. Experiences include story time, healthy sandwich making, drawing, clay moulding, seedling planting and more. 

In line with this year's focus of the right of every child having the right to speak and be heard they will have opportunities for children and families to talk about and document their thoughts, ideas and hopes for their local community. &#160; 
&#160; 
Time: 9.30 am - 12.30 pm

Every child&#39;s favourite event is back, the Wodonga Children&#39;s Fair. 

The aim of the event is to celebrate families and young people, and to acknowledge the huge effort that families put into raising children to be active and healthy and make positive contributions to their community&#39;s well-being. 

Wodonga Children&#39;s Fair is open to all families, giving them the opportunity to spend time together at an event where they can be entertained, informed, engaged, educated and most importantly have fun.

Stepping back in time, this year the Wodonga Children&#39;s Fair theme will be &#39;games of yesteryear&#39;, focusing on games and activities from the years gone by.

Over 120 community organisations will come together for this event. Program highlights for 2014:

- Bananas in Pyjamas - come and have your photo taken with them;
- Steve Bowen
- Wild Action - children can get &#39;close-up&#39; to Australian native fauna;
- Learn the heel and toe polka with the Bungowannah Bush Band;
- Hands-on touching &amp; feeling of dinosaur casts, real fossils, live bugs, playing federation handbells &amp; playing memories of childhood games with Museum Victoria;
- Cuddle a farm animal in the Animal Play area; and
- Green Hat Workshops - technical building blocks designed to inspire creative minds;
- Emergency Service display vehicles.

Time: 10am to 3pm
Ph: (02) 6022 9300

Dawn to Dusk; Landscapes from the CBus collection of Australian Art.

Representations of Australian landscape by non-indigenous artists could be described as a gradual shift from a European sense of light in colonial times, to recognition of the particularities and clarity of Australian light by artists working in the twentieth century. This exhibition focuses on the quality of light and colour in the Australian landscape.

The title for this exhibition came from the recognition that colour and light is shown to great effect and stunning clarity in both the rising and setting of the sun. As Thomas Cole once said &quot;the sky is the soul of all scenery. It makes the earth lovely at sunrise and splendid at sunset. In the one it breathes over the earth a crystal-like ether, in the other a liquid gold.&quot;
